  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering at both the national and international levels. Here are some key examples:\n\n### United States\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970** - Also known as the Currency and Foreign Transactions Reporting Act, this law requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports that could be useful in detecting and preventing money laundering.\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** - This act makes money laundering a federal crime and imposes severe penalties. It also requires financial institutions to report suspicious activities.\n3. **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001** - This act expanded the scope of the BSA and introduced stricter regulations to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. It includes provisions for enhanced due diligence and monitoring of foreign accounts.\n\n### European Union\n1. **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** - The EU has issued several directives aimed at combating money laundering and terrorist financing. The most recent is the 6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD), which harmonizes definitions and penalties across member states.\n2. **Regulation (EU) 2015/847** - This regulation requires information on payers and payees to be transmitted alongside transfers of funds.\n\n### International\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** - Although not a statute, FATF sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Its recommendations are adopted by many countries around the world.\n2. **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** - Commonly known as the Vienna Convention, this treaty includes provisions against money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n3. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** - Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes measures to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n\n### Other Countries\n1. **Canada** - The Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act (PCMLTFA) is the primary legislation.\n2. **United Kingdom** - The Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA) is the main legislation, supplemented by the Money Laundering Regulations.\n3. **Australia** - The Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorism Financing Act 2006 (AML/CTF Act) is the key legislation.\n\nThese statutes and regulations are continually updated to address emerging threats and improve the effectiveness of anti-money laundering efforts.",
